### Parser Trait Documentation

Source: https://docs.rs/clap/latest/clap/trait.Parser_search=std%3A%3Avec

The `Parser` trait is a convenience trait that combines `FromArgMatches` and `CommandFactory` to facilitate parsing command-line arguments into a concrete struct. It provides methods to parse arguments from standard input or custom iterators, with options to exit on error or return a `Result`.

```APIDOC
## Trait Parser

### Description
Parse command-line arguments into `Self`. The primary one-stop-shop trait used to create an instance of a `clap` `Command`, conduct the parsing, and turn the resulting `ArgMatches` back into concrete instance of the user struct. This trait is primarily a convenience on top of `FromArgMatches` + `CommandFactory` which uses those two underlying traits to build the two fundamental functions `parse` which uses the `std::env::args_os` iterator, and `parse_from` which allows the consumer to supply the iterator (along with fallible options for each).

**NOTE:** Deriving requires the `derive` feature flag.

### Provided Methods

#### fn parse() -> Self

##### Description
Parse from `std::env::args_os()`, exit on error.

##### Examples
```rust
// examples/typed-derive/main.rs (line 20)
fn main() {
    let cli = Cli::parse();
    println!("{cli:?}");
}
```
```rust
// examples/derive_ref/flatten_hand_args.rs (line 89)
fn main() {
    let args = Cli::parse();
    println!("{args:#?}");
}
```

#### fn try_parse() -> Result<Self, Error>

##### Description
Parse from `std::env::args_os()`, return Err on error.

#### fn parse_from<I, T>(itr: I) -> Self

##### Description
Parse from iterator, exit on error.

##### Type Parameters
* `I`: Must implement `IntoIterator<Item = T>`
* `T`: Must implement `Into<OsString> + Clone`

#### fn try_parse_from<I, T>(itr: I) -> Result<Self, Error>

##### Description
Parse from iterator, return Err on error.

##### Type Parameters
* `I`: Must implement `IntoIterator<Item = T>`
* `T`: Must implement `Into<OsString> + Clone`

##### Examples
```rust
// examples/repl-derive.rs (line 31)
fn respond(line: &str) -> Result<bool, String> {
    let args = shlex::split(line).ok_or("error: Invalid quoting")?;
    let cli = Cli::try_parse_from(args).map_err(|e| e.to_string())?;
    // ... (rest of the example)
    Ok(false)
}
```
